        "title": "Experimental shear failure of reinforced concrete beams in fire conditions",
        "published": "2026-06-30",
        "url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.engstruct.2026.123055",
        "authors": [
          "Sabine Boulvard",
          "Duc Toan Pham",
          "Jérémy Bleyer"
        ],
        "institutions": [
          "Centre National de la Recherche Scientifique",
          "Centre Scientifique et Technique du Bâtiment",
          "Laboratoire Navier",
          "Université Gustave Eiffel"
        ],
        "journal": "Engineering Structures",
        "abstract": "This paper presents the results of a test campaign of twelve reinforced concrete beams without transverse reinforcements under four-point bending and thermal loading in order to achieve their shear failure in fire conditions. Midspan deflection, temperature, shear strength and crack angle of the beams were measured throughout the campaign. Furthermore, the experimental shear strength of the beams at ambient temperature was compared to predictions from ACI Code-318–25 and EN 1992–1–1. Then, the experimental shear strength of the beams in fire conditions was compared to predictions from EN 1992–1–2 and those derived from a design model based on the upper bound kinematic approach of the yield design theory. Such comparisons were made using different values of the effectiveness factor applied to the compressive strength of concrete, available in the literature, making it possible to show the influence of such a factor on the comparative results.",
        "citation_count": 0,
        "method": "Hybrid"
      },
      {
        "id": "https://openalex.org/W7166552205",
        "doi": "10.1016/j.engstruct.2026.123243",
        "title": "Wind–vehicle–bridge interaction and driving safety reliability under skew winds",
        "published": "2026-06-29",
        "url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.engstruct.2026.123243",
        "authors": [
          "Alfredo Cámara",
          "Chetan Jagadeesh",
          "S. Divall"
        ],
        "institutions": [
          "Universidad Politécnica de Madrid",
          "Northampton Community College",
          "City, University of London"
        ],
        "journal": "Engineering Structures",
        "abstract": "Wind-induced vehicle accidents on bridges depend not only on mean wind speed but also on turbulence and pavement roughness. Existing wind–vehicle–bridge interaction (W-VBI) studies typically rely on a limited number of stochastic wind and pavement realisations, restricting the quantification of record-to-record variability in driving safety. This study proposes a W-VBI framework that explicitly embeds this variability into the driving safety assessment. Applied to a twin box-girder bridge, the methodology combines stochastic simulations of turbulent wind and pavement profiles with aerodynamic coefficients obtained from wind-tunnel tests, which are used to define wind loads in the coupled W-VBI analysis. Over 85,000 nonlinear simulations are conducted for 11 wind angles, five gust levels, two high-sided vehicles, and speeds from 15–130 km/h. Vehicle overturning, side-slipping, and yawing probabilities are calculated, using bootstrapping techniques to evaluate the statistical stability of the simulations. Results show that wind and pavement randomness induce significant record-to-record variability in vehicle safety, while bootstrapping enables estimation of the minimum number of stochastic records required for statistically stable reliability assessments.",
        "citation_count": 0,
        "method": "Numerical Simulation"
      }
    ],
